
[1]ornament

   OR'NAMENT, n. [L. ornamentum, from orno, to adorn. Varro informs us
   that this was primitively osnamentum; but this is improbable. See
   Adorn.]

   1. That which embellishes; something which, added to another thing,
   renders it more beautiful to the eye.

   The chains, and the bracelets, and the mufflers, the bonnets and the
   ornaments of the legs - Is. 3.

   2. In architecture, ornaments are sculpture or carved work.

   3. Embellishment; decoration; additional beauty.

   - The ornament of a meek and quiet spirit which is in the sight of God
   of great price. 1Peter 3.

              OR'NAMENT, v.t. To adorn; to deck; to embellish.
